traits are strictly Mendelian.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>The parental generation must be both heterozygotes as at least one child is Blonde (bb). So your cross is <strong>Bb<\/strong> x <strong>Bb<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Your square is going to look like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>           _B_            _b_\n\n_B_         BB           Bb\n\n\n\n_b_         bB           bb\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>So of the question is:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>What is the probability that Q is heterozygous?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The PhD is <strong>INCORRECT<\/strong>. They probably just made a simple Punnet Square in their head and forgot the caveat that you have to exclude \"<strong>bb<\/strong>\" because Q is <em>not<\/em> Blonde. The possible allele combinations for <strong>non-Blonde<\/strong> offspring from a Heterozygotic cross are only <strong>BB, bB, Bb<\/strong>. <\/p>\n\n<p>Therefor the probability that <strong>Q<\/strong> is <em>Heterozygous<\/em> is indeed 2/3 (<strong>bB, Bb<\/strong>).<\/p>\n\n<p>It's not uncommon for PhD students - who are often deep into their own research - to gloss over details and possibly give incorrect answers because the information hasn't been relevant to them for years (most traits <em>aren't<\/em> Mendelian, strictly recessive or dominant, and rarely involve a single allele), so give them some slack unless they were being a jerk about it. =)<\/p>\n","answer_id":8022,"question_id":8021,"up_vote_count":7}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/8021/two-brown-haired-people-have-two-children-p-and-q-p-has-blond-hair-q-has-brow","last_activity_date":1366563601,"creation_date":1366558808,"answer_count":1,"title":"Two brown-haired people have two children, P and Q. P has blond hair. Q has brown hair. What is the probability that Q is heterozygous?","body":"<p>Two brown-haired people have two children, P and Q. P has blond hair. We therefore believe that each parent is heterozygous and that blond hair is a recessive trait.\nQ has brown hair. What is the probability that Q is heterozygous?<\/p>\n\n<p>My answer:  2/3.  There are four possibilities Bb, bB, BB,and bb. Before observing the color of Q's hair, we assign equal chance to each.  We eliminate bb as a possibility.  The chance that it is bB or Bb and not BB is 2/3.<\/p>\n\n<p>A Biology PhD disagrees with me and says that the probability is 1/2. Who is right?<\/p>\n","question_id":8021,"tags":["genetics","homework","statistics"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":8022,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":264,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1366562049},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0syJT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1813,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1813/brenton-horne","reputation":1198,"display_name":"Brenton Horne","accept_rate":32},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24c0e23c30888c23e2d4fe9991cf2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":57,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/57/jonsca","reputation":3367,"display_name":"jonsca","accept_rate":100},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0syJT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1813,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1813/brenton-horne","reputation":1198,"display_name":"Brenton Horne","accept_rate":32},"score":0,"post_id":7951,"edited":false,"creation_date":1366243033,"comment_id":10079,"body":"Where exactly on this site do you find the PD and PK data? I looked up sertraline all I got was these sort of pages...<a href=\"http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cder/drugsatfda/index.cfm?fuseaction=Search.Overview\" rel=\"nofollow\">accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cder/drugsatfda/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24c0e23c30888c23e2d4fe9991cf2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":57,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com