f celestial objects to measure the relative time, but regardless of these external cues, I suspect that a pretty good internal clock for longer time scale could exist. For example, the time to menopause can actually be thought of as a counting mechanism of a shorter clock which is the menstrual cycle. But, how does the body know when to stop growing? I cannot think of biological processes with such long time constants that is stable.<\/p>\n","question_id":3590,"tags":["physiology"],"score":12,"accepted_answer_id":3609,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":265,"up_vote_count":12,"last_edit_date":1348046086},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/47028ffaabe988b80f28db0301cb6da6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3389/rht","reputation":129,"display_name":"RHT"},"closed_date":1366067423,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"post_id":7915,"edited":false,"creation_date":1366067401,"comment_id":10018,"body":"This has effectively been superseded by your subsequent question - in future you might want to consider using the <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/posts/7915/edit\">edit<\/a> function :)"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7915/do-the-antlers-re-grow-in-the-same-pattern-every-year","last_activity_date":1366051979,"creation_date":1366051979,"answer_count":0,"title":"Do the antlers re-grow in the same pattern every year?","body":"<p>I am a software engineer and I am trying to develop a system to identify a deer by its photograph.<\/p>\n\n<p>Most deers lose their antlers every year. I would like to know if they re-grow in the same pattern next year and if yes, then what are the measurements that are of interest here?<\/p>\n\