denaturation/chemical modification, as likely happens with people who are allergic to things like isopropanol or bleach.<\/p>\n\n<p>I very much doubt that there can be such a thing as a glucose allergy, as it is so ubiquitous in the body that such antibodies/T-cells would be <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_selection_%28immunology%29\">negatively selected<\/a> long before they could do any damage.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7910,"question_id":7905,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7905/what-is-the-smallest-molecule-that-can-present-as-an-antigen-to-the-immune-syste","last_activity_date":1366039069,"creation_date":1365999318,"answer_count":2,"title":"What is the smallest molecule that can present as an antigen to the immune system in the context of allergies?","body":"<p>People often claim, in a colloquial sense, that they are \"allergic to everything\".  <\/p>\n\n<p>Is it possible to have a full-fledged IgE mediated allergic response to very small molecules?  I was always under the impression that the smallest antigen was a oligopeptide, but is it possible for someone to be allergic to something like isopropanol, glucose, or another small organic molecule?  <\/p>\n\n<p>How about allergies to metals, as I know those are fairly common, would they be mediated through a similar mechanism?<\/p>\n","question_id":7905,"tags":["immunology","allergies"],"score":8,"accepted_answer_id":7910,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":569,"up_vote_count":9},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1e5c2468b26cc8a209c909e52942e9e8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3385,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3385/kaish","reputation":111,"display_name":"Kaish"},"closed_date":1366071398,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/OxfyD.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3059,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3059/dd3","reputation":