y has a point. In fact, organelle concentration is very different even in different parts of a single cell. E.g. the axon terminals of neurons contain a lof ot mitochondria to provide ATP for continuous firing, while the cell soma (the main body, which can be more than 1m away) contains much fewer of them. Another case, most cells only have one nucleus. Certain cell types like skeletal and cardiac muscle or the placental trophoblasts however fuse and form multinucleated cells."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/39b7eb876a5036084ea54aecc1b888b1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3338/rrs-ghost","reputation":170,"display_name":"RRs_Ghost","accept_rate":40},"score":0,"post_id":7756,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"edited":false,"creation_date":1365104459,"comment_id":9734,"body":"@terdon I am aware that there are many different types of organelle. I am interested in the range of the total number of organelle (from the simplest cell to the most complex)"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a43651dba3f306d9c0c0b92a7457722?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1441,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1441/bitwise","reputation":1705,"display_name":"Bitwise"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/39b7eb876a5036084ea54aecc1b888b1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3338/rrs-ghost","reputation":170,"display_name":"RRs_Ghost","accept_rate":40},"score":0,"post_id":7775,"edited":false,"creation_date":1365199118,"comment_id":9761,"body":"Thanks! exactly what I was looking 