/users/3261/relf20","reputation":709,"display_name":"relf20"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1364973639,"creation_date":1364973639,"body":"<p>Use <a href=\"http://www.promega.com/~/media/Files/Resources/Protocols/Technical%20Manuals/0/pGEM-T%20and%20pGEM-T%20Easy%20Vector%20Systems%20Protocol.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">pGemT<\/a> to clone your PCR product into. It is exactly designed to take products with 3' overhangs and features blue/white selection so is pretty easy to do! Then you would cut out of pGem with the restriction sites you added during your PCR and ligate it into your expression vector.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7745,"question_id":7739,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7739/how-prevalent-is-taq-polymerase-in-adding-3-a-overhangs-to-the-pcr-product","last_activity_date":1365026612,"creation_date":1364929652,"answer_count":2,"title":"How prevalent is Taq polymerase in adding 3' A overhangs to the PCR product?","body":"<p>I am conducting a mutagenesis on a gene in vivo of which I need to ligate into an expression vector.  The primers I have designed overlap restriction sites of which I plan to use to ligate into the expression vector.  The parts between the primers I will try to create mutants with error prone PCR.<\/p>\n\n<p>My concern is the 3' A overhangs that are created from Taq polymerase.  How prevalent is this?  If it is highly common, what is the best way to account for these additions when trying to ligate my PCR product into the vector?<\/p>\n","question_id":7739,"tags":["pcr","experimental-design","restriction-enzymes"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":7740,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1048,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2a86abedcc965c216d0e0d39dd7a6644?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3090,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3090/abigailb55","reputation":48,"display_name":"Abigailb55"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1365004068,"creation_date":1365004068,"body":"<p>The phosphoryl transfer potential is one way to think about the free energy available to do useful work when ATP is hydrolysed. <\/p>\n\n<p>As you can see from the free energy equation below, a positive change in entropy will help to decrease (i.e. make more negative) the free energy change. <\/p>\n\n<p>This is why an endothermic reaction can still occur spontaneously if the entropy change is big enough to create an entropy term that outweighs the enthalpy term in the Gibbs free energy equation.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>&Delta;G=&Delta;H - T&Delta;S<\/p>\n  \n  <p>where:<br>\n  T= temperature<br>\n  G = Gibbs free energy<br>\n  H = enthalpy<br>\n  S = entropy<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":7749,"question_id":7731,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7731/why-does-the-hydrolysis-of-atp-increasing-entropy-increase-the-phosphoryl-tran","last_activity_date":1365004068,"creation_date":1364866448,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why does the hydrolysis of ATP increasing entropy increase the Phosphoryl-­\u2010transfer Potential?","body":"<p>I am currently taking a biology class. I do not understand this concept. I understand that the electrostatic repulsion of the negative charges, resonance stabilization and hydration stabilization all contribute. However, I do not understand why an increase in entropy would help. Wouldn't it be more favorable to have less entropy in a system?<\/p>\n","question_id":7731,"tags":["molecular-biology","metabolism","thermodynamics"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":941,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1364876392},{"own