m/users/3059/dd3","reputation":2303,"display_name":"dd3","accept_rate":95},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1364536835,"creation_date":1364536835,"body":"<p>@LanceLafontaine suggested a few ways above, but I would recommend reading <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK26818/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this section<\/a>\nin Alberts' Molecular Biology of the Cell, which gives a more descriptive overview of some approaches, but even that is not exhaustive.<\/p>\n\n<p>An extremely simplistic and also not exhaustive summary:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>observe mutants, see what processes are disrupted, and map these back to particular mutations<\/li>\n<li>mutate a gene and see what processes are disrupted<\/li>\n<li>biochemical studies to see, for example, which proteins (which are gene products) interact <em>in vivo<\/em> and things like where they're localized, which may hint at function.<\/li>\n<li>analyze structure of proteins, see <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homology_%28biology%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">how similar they are to other proteins<\/a> with known function, and infer that the protein of interest probably has a similar function<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>EDIT: The link to Alberts is to the 2002 edition (which is free online; the latest edition of the textbook costs around $200), so things have come a long way since then, but the underlying approaches are still in use.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7695,"question_id":7694,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7694/how-are-geneticists-able-to-isolate-gene-functions","last_activity_date":1364536835,"creation_date":1364526014,"answer_count":1,"title":"How are geneticists able to isolate gene functions?","body":"<p>As an example, this <a href=\"http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/2013/01/24/adaptation-to-starchy-diet-was-key-to-dog-domestication\" rel=\"nofollow\">Scientific American article<\/a> describes a known area in the dog genome that metabolizes carbohydrates.  <\/p>\n\n<p>How is it that researchers are able to determine specific functions such as this?<\/p>\n","question_id":7694,"tags":["genetics","genomics","dna-sequencing"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":53,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1364526622},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7e5775439438b07b6f14a697a17dc49b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":541,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/541/blunders","reputation":119,"display_name":"blunders"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":2,"post_id":2351,"edited":false,"creation_date":1337717590,"comment_id":3177,"body":"It&#39;s not really clear what &#39;factors of evolution&#39; you are referring to... there are many factors that play a role in evolution - availability of nutrients, availability of reproductive partners, space,... Could you clarify a bit what kind of factors you mean?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7e5775439438b07b6f14a697a17dc49b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":541,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/541/blunders","reputation":119,"display_name":"blunders"},"score":0,"post_id":2351,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"edited":false,"creation_date":1337718103,"comment_id":3179,"body":"@Armatus: &quot;availability of nutrients&quot; would be an environmental change. I&#39;m not sure about &quot;availability of reproductive partn